05:29.540 --> 05:32.100
And we go through this thing called the Krebs cycle.

05:32.100 --> 05:35.980
And the Krebs cycle is basically pulling out CO2 and hydrogen.

05:35.980 --> 05:38.100
That's all I really want you to get from this.

05:38.100 --> 05:41.980
CO2 is a way of breathing it out into the atmosphere,

05:41.980 --> 05:44.500
contributing our own little bit to global warming.

05:44.500 --> 05:47.820
And the hydrogen, while we're splitting the hydrogen,

05:47.820 --> 05:49.620
the hydrogen atoms, two hydrogen atoms,

05:49.620 --> 05:52.420
we're splitting them into their fundamental parts,

05:52.420 --> 05:54.260
the electrons and the protons.

05:54.340 --> 05:58.940
We have a current of electrons going to oxygen.

05:58.940 --> 06:01.020
That current of electrons,

06:01.020 --> 06:04.900
literally pretty much an electric wire inside this membrane,

06:04.900 --> 06:06.260
inside this insulated membrane,

06:06.260 --> 06:10.460
is powering the extrusion of protons across the membrane.

06:10.460 --> 06:13.740
So now we have a lot of protons on this side of the membrane,

06:13.740 --> 06:16.140
very few protons on the inside.

06:16.140 --> 06:17.900
About three orders of magnitude difference,

06:17.900 --> 06:20.780
three pH units difference.

06:20.780 --> 06:23.740
Now that may not seem like very much.

06:23.740 --> 06:29.220
